Introduction
************

   There is no bugs mailing list for Geek Gadgets yet. Please report
bugs to @{b}gg@ninemoons.com@{ub}, or to the author directly. Remember to include
the version number, machine architecture, input files, and any other
information needed to reproduce the bug: your input, what you expected,
what you got, and why it is wrong.  Diffs are welcome, but please
include a description of the problem as well, since this is sometimes
difficult to infer. See @{"Bugs" link "gcc.guide/Bugs"}.

   This package is based on the net2 and later BSD distributions. The
original Geek Gadgets distribution of man-1.0 from Geek Gadgets
snapshots up to and including 961012 was put together from the
4.3BSD-net2 distribution. The files were downloaded from
@{b}sunsite.doc.ic.ac.uk@{ub} from the directories
computing/operating-systems/unix/bsd-sources/usr.bin/man and
computing/operating-systems/unix/bsd-sources/usr.bin/whereis and
computing/operating-systems/unix/bsd-sources/share/man/makewhatis.sed.Z.
Hans Verkuil @{b}hans@wyst.hobby.nl@{ub} enhanced the sources and fixed several
bugs. He rewrote the makewhatis script completely in perl for speed.

   Then the distribution was restructured to adopt the common GNU
XXX-utils package layout. The programs apropos, man and whatis were
taken from NetBSD-current, and the distribution renamed to manutils-2.0.
Later, @{b}catman.pl@{ub} and @{b}makewhatis.pl@{ub} were added from FreeBSD, which in
turn required the addition of the @{b}col@{ub} program from NetBSD-current. The
programs have been modified to take care of Amiga specific issues. The
package is currently maintained by Lars Hecking @{b}lhecking@ninemoons.com@{ub}.

   This manual is based on the Unix man pages in the distribution, which
were originally written at the University of California in Berkeley.
The man pages for the catman.pl and makewhatis.pl perl scripts were
written by and are copyrighted by Wolfram Schneider @{b}wosch@FreeBSD.org@{ub}.
Lars Hecking put all this into Texinfo format, did the indexing, wrote
the package specific chapters, and also contributed his usual
invaluable insights to the overall process.


@endnode

