Conventions and environment
***************************

   Unless stated otherwise, all utilities assume Unix path name
conventions. Directory lists are separated by a colon @{b}:@{ub}.

   The following environment variables affect the execution of the
manual utilities. Note that the preference setting @{b}ignore global
environment@{ub} for @{b}ixemul.library@{ub} may cause the man utilities to ignore
the variables. If @{b}ixemul.library@{ub} is configured to ignore the global
environment (@{b}ENV:@{ub}), these variables must be @{b}set@{ub} locally in every shell
(or in @{b}S:Shell-Startup@{ub} on the Amiga).

@{b}MANPATH@{ub}
     a colon (@{b}:@{ub}) separated list of directories. If set, its value
     overrides @{b}/GG/man@{ub} as the default directory search path, and the
     @{b}man.cf@{ub} file as the default section search path. The @{b}-M@{ub} flag, in
     turn, overrides these values. It is normally not required to set
     this variable.

@{b}PAGER@{ub}
     a program to use for interactively delivering man's output to the
     screen. If not set, @{b}less -e@{ub} is used.

@{b}TERM@{ub}
     the @{b}TERM@{ub} environment variable is not used by manutils directly,
     but by the default pager @{b}less@{ub}. It should be set to @{b}amiga@{ub}.

@{b}LESS@{ub}
     the @{b}LESS@{ub} environment variable is not used by manutils directly,
     but by the default pager @{b}less@{ub}. @{b}Less@{ub} takes it's options from @{b}LESS@{ub}.

@{b}LESSCHARSET@{ub}
     the @{b}LESSCHARSET@{ub} environment variable is not used by manutils
     directly, but by the default pager @{b}less@{ub}. It should be set to
     @{b}latin1@{ub} to display all of the ISO-8859-1 character set.

   There are many more environment variables for @{b}less@{ub}.  Please refer to
the online manual for @{b}less@{ub}.


@endnode

