Installation
************

   For detailed installation instructions, please refer to the @{b}INSTALL@{ub}
and @{b}README@{ub} file in the top directory of the source distribution.

   Normally, the following steps will be taken to configure, compile and
install the distribution:

  1. Run @{b}configure@{ub} to configure the package for your system. Type
     @{b}configure --help@{ub} to see a list of supported options.

  2. Type @{b}make@{ub} to compile the package. You may want to look at the
     @{b}Makefile@{ub} generated by @{b}configure@{ub} to adjust compiler flags etc.

  3. Type @{b}make install@{ub} to install the programs and any data files and
     documentation.

   Before compiling manutils, various defaults can be set in
@{b}lib/defs.h@{ub}. Some of these should not be modified, though, they are
merely listed for completeness. Others can be configured at run time
through @{b}man.conf@{ub}.

@{b}_PATH_MANCONF@{ub}
     The path to the @{b}man.conf@{ub} configuration file. The default is
     @{b}/GG/etc/man.conf@{ub}.

@{b}_PATH_PAGER@{ub}
     The name of the pager program used by @{b}man@{ub}. The default is @{b}less -e@{ub}.
     @{b}Less@{ub} is available in several different distributions, it is not
     part of manutils.

@{b}_PATH_TMP@{ub}
     The template file name for temporary files created by @{b}man@{ub}.  The
     default is @{b}/tmp/man.XXXXXX@{ub}.

@{b}_PATH_WHATIS@{ub}
     The name of the whatis database file. The default is @{b}whatis.db@{ub}.

@{b}UPDATE_FORMAT@{ub}
     The @{b}UPDATE_FORMAT@{ub} macro controls whether formatted manual pages
     should be compressed with @{b}gzip@{ub}. It has two possible values:
     @{b}UPDATE_FORMAT_GZIP@{ub} (default), and @{b}UPADTE_FORMAT_PLAIN@{ub}. The @{b}gzip@{ub}
     program is available in a separate distribution.

@{b}GZIP_SUFFIX@{ub}
     The suffix for files compressed with @{b}gzip@{ub}. It defaults to @{b}.gz@{ub}.
     There is normally no need to change this.

@{b}GZIP_NAME@{ub}
     The name of the @{b}gzip@{ub} program. It defaults to @{b}gzip@{ub}.  There is
     normally no need to change this.

@{b}NROFF_COMMAND@{ub}
     The name and command line arguments of the @{b}nroff@{ub} formatter.  The
     default is @{b}nroff -Tascii -mandoc %s@{ub}.

   The macro @{b}IX_TO_AMIGA_PATH@{ub} in @{b}lib/defs.h@{ub} is used in various places
to transform Unix style path names into AmigaDOS style path names. It's
main purpose is to simplify interfacing to native AmigaDOS programs,
which do not understand Unix path name conventions. It should not be
changed.


@endnode

