Locate command
**************

   The @{b}Whereis@{ub} program locates source/binary and manuals sections for
specified files. The supplied names are first stripped of leading
pathname components and of any (single) trailing extension of the form
@{b}.ext@{ub}, e.g. @{b}.c@{ub}. Prefixes of @{b}s.@{ub} resulting from use of source code control
are also dealt with. @{b}Whereis@{ub} then attempts to locate the desired
program in a list of standard places.

   For the future, it is planned to rewrite whereis to support long
options and database lookup.


 @{" whereis options        " link "whereis options"}  Options for whereis.
 @{" whereis invocation     " link "whereis invocation"}  Invocation and examples.


@endnode

@node "whereis options" "manutils.guide/whereis options"
@next "whereis invocation"
@toc "Locate command"

@{b}whereis@{ub} options
===============

   Available options:

@{b}-b@{ub}
     Search for binaries.

@{b}-f@{ub}
     Signals the end of a directory list specified by one or more of the
     @{b}-B@{ub}, @{b}-M@{ub} or @{b}-S@{ub} options and the start of file names.

@{b}-m@{ub}
     Search for manual entries.

@{b}-s@{ub}
     Search for source.

@{b}-u@{ub}
     Search for unusual entries. A file is said to be unusual if it
     does not have one entry of each requested type. Thus:
          whereis -m -u *
     asks for those files in the current directory which have no
     documentation.

@{b}-B@{ub}
     Change or limit directories searched for binaries. Requires the @{b}-f@{ub}
     flag.

@{b}-M@{ub}
     Change or limit directories searched for manual entries. Requires
     the @{b}-f@{ub} flag.

@{b}-S@{ub}
     Change or limit directories searched for source. Requires the @{b}-f@{ub}
     flag.


@endnode

@node "whereis invocation" "manutils.guide/whereis invocation"
@prev "whereis options"
@toc "Locate command"

@{b}whereis@{ub} invocation
==================

   Synopsis:
     $ whereis [OPTIONS]... [KEYWORD]...

   The following finds all the files in @{b}/usr/bin@{ub} which are not
documented in @{b}/usr/share/man/man1@{ub} with source in @{b}/usr/src/cmd@{ub}:
     whereis -u -M /usr/share/man/man1 -S /usr/src/cmd -f *


