Utility programs
****************

   Utility programs used by man.

@{b}   Col@{ub} filters out reverse (and half reverse) line feeds so that the
output is in the correct order with only forward and half forward line
feeds, and replaces white-space characters with tabs where possible.
This can be useful in processing the output of @{b}nroff@{ub} and @{b}tbl@{ub}.


 @{" col options               " link "col options"}  Options for col.
 @{" col invocation            " link "col invocation"}  Invocation and examples.


@endnode

@node "col options" "manutils.guide/col options"
@next "col invocation"
@toc "Utility programs"

@{b}col@{ub} options
===========

@{b}-b@{ub}
     Do not output any backspaces, printing only the last character
     written to each column position.

@{b}-f@{ub}
     Forward half line feeds are permitted (@{b}fine@{ub} mode).  Normally
     characters printed on a half line boundary are printed on the
     following line.

@{b}-x@{ub}
     Output multiple spaces instead of tabs.

@{b}-l @{b}num@{ub}@{ub}
     Buffer at least @{b}num@{ub} lines in memory. By default, 128 lines are
     buffered.

   The control sequences for carriage motion that @{b}col@{ub} understands and
their decimal values are listed in the following table:

@{b}ESC-7@{ub}
     reverse line feed (escape then 7)

@{b}ESC-8@{ub}
     half reverse line feed (escape then 8)

@{b}ESC-9@{ub}
     half forward line feed (escape then 9)

@{b}backspace@{ub}
     moves back one column (8); ignored in the first column

@{b}carriage return (13)@{ub}

@{b}newline@{ub}
     forward line feed (10); also does carriage return

@{b}shift in@{ub}
     shift to normal character set (15)

@{b}shift out@{ub}
     shift to alternate character set (14)

@{b}space@{ub}
     moves forward one column (32)

@{b}tab@{ub}
     moves forward to next tab stop (9)

@{b}vertical tab@{ub}
     reverse line feed (11)

   All unrecognized control characters and escape sequences are
discarded.

@{b}   Col@{ub} keeps track of the character set as characters are read and
makes sure the character set is correct when they are output.

   If the input attempts to back up to the last flushed line, @{b}col@{ub} will
display a warning message.


@endnode

@node "col invocation" "manutils.guide/col invocation"
@prev "col options"
@toc "Utility programs"

@{b}col@{ub} invocation
==============

   The @{b}col@{ub} program is invoked by @{b}man@{ub}, @{b}catman.pl@{ub} and @{b}makewhatis.pl@{ub}.
There is normally no need to invoke @{b}col@{ub} from the command line.


@endnode

