@node "FAQ" "manutils.guide/FAQ"
@toc "Tips and tricks"

FAQ
===

   * Q1.1 @{b}man man@{ub} doesn't work, it says @{b}cannot create@{ub}.
     You are running an outdated version of @{b}man@{ub} from ADE snapshot
     961012 or earlier. Upgrade to version 2.1 or later.

   * Q1.2 Can't use another pager for @{b}man@{ub}.
     If you get @{b}sh: less: not found@{ub}, then $PAGER is not set correctly.
     Depending on the preferences setting for @{b}ixemul.library@{ub}, you may
     need to set the local variable, not the global (@{b}ENV:PAGER@{ub}) one:
     @{b}Set PAGER `Which MultiView`@{ub}. Note the backtics!

     As of manutils version 2.1, pathnames passed to external programs
     obey Amiga path conventions.

   * Q1.3 Formatted man pages are unreadable in Multiview.
     Formatted man pages may still contain bold and underlined
     characters, which make them a bit unreadable in MultiView. There
     is a man datatype on Aminet which takes care of this.

   * Q1.4 Can't use @{b}less@{ub} as @{b}man's@{ub} pager.
     It is essential that the @{b}TERM@{ub} and @{b}LESSCHARSET@{ub} environment
     variables are set up properly. See @{"Conventions and environment" link "Conventions and environment"}.

     It may be better to use a different pager, eg. @{b}MultiView@{ub} or
     @{b}Less-1.6Z@{ub} from Aminet (?).

   * Q1.5 The manual datatype is not working.
     This is not a manutils bug. The manual datatype can only display
     formatted manual pages (those that contain codes like
     m^H_a^H^_n^H_) but not unformatted (nroff) ones (containing
     sequences like .SH, .TH etc.). Unfortunately, most UNIX archives
     come with unformatted manual pages.

     Use the @{b}catman.pl@{ub} perl script or @{b}man@{ub}'s @{b}-u@{ub} (@{b}--update@{ub}) option.

   * Q1.6 @{b}Man@{ub} crashes
     Make sure you have @{b}ixemul.library@{ub} version 45.1 or later, and that
     the @{b}man@{ub} program has sufficient stack (32k), either by setting
     @{b}ixstack@{ub}, or setting the stack of the invoking shell.

   * Q1.7 @{b}Man@{ub} doesn't automatically create formatted pages.
     No relesed version of man/manutils for ADE/Geek Gadgets ever did.
     That's what the @{b}-u@{ub} (@{b}--update@{ub}) switch is for.

   * Q1.8 @{b}Man@{ub} generates a gzip'ed version of the formatted page.
     This is the default behaviour. It can be switched off at compile
     time only, see the chapter about installation.

   * Q1.9 @{b}Man@{ub} creates weird output.
          m$<>NAMEm$<>
                 less - opposite of more
          
          m$<>SYNOPSISm$<>
                 m$<>lessm$<> m$<>-?m$<>
                 m$<>lessm$<> m$<>-Vm$<>
                 m$<>lessm$<> m$<>[-[+]aBcCdeEfgGiImMnNqQrsSuUVwX]m$<>
                      m$<>[-bm$<> m$<>bufsm$<>m$<>]m$<> m$<>[-hm$<>

     This may happen if the pager (normally @{b}less@{ub}) is linked against
     ncurses. Deleting the @{b}$HOME/.terminfo@{ub} directory normally helps.

   * Q1.10 sh: /bin/nroff: not found
     To be fully functional, @{b}man@{ub} requires that the groff package is
     installed.


@endnode

